00:53:09,720 --> 00:53:12,189
Alright, I went to look at a car.

738
00:53:12,190 --> 00:53:14,149
- With Shelby?
- With Shelby.

739
00:53:14,149 --> 00:53:16,404
- A racing car?
- Sort of.

740
00:53:17,596 --> 00:53:20,068
There's a corner coming,
you better hold on.

741
00:53:20,815 --> 00:53:23,361
Mol, are you gonna lift your foot off
at all through this?

742
00:53:23,362 --> 00:53:25,111
No. 'Cause I like a clean racing line.

743
00:53:25,112 --> 00:53:26,729
Slow down!

744
00:53:30,576 --> 00:53:34,171
Okay. Shel offered me a job.
Ford has a car

745
00:53:34,171 --> 00:53:36,428
that they wanna put up
against Ferrari.

746
00:53:36,428 --> 00:53:40,110
- You told me you were done!
- I didn't say yes!

747
00:53:40,437 --> 00:53:42,905
- Slow down!
- You told me you quit!

748
00:53:44,025 --> 00:53:46,364
- I don't understand.
- Get fat and old you said!

749
00:53:46,502 --> 00:53:48,533
Fat and old!

750
00:53:51,981 --> 00:53:53,612
<i>- I don't understand.</i>
- That's what you told me!

751
00:53:53,612 --> 00:53:55,151
I don't understand.

752
00:53:55,453 --> 00:53:59,864
Are you upset because I said I was done
or because I looked at a race car?

753
00:54:01,170 --> 00:54:03,829
Just don't lie to me again!

754
00:54:05,374 --> 00:54:08,482
Don't make it a secret,
what you want or what you feel

755
00:54:08,482 --> 00:54:11,721
just because you think
it's gonna make me happy!

756
00:54:13,344 --> 00:54:15,936
Mol, I don't even know what I feel.

757
00:54:22,621 --> 00:54:24,635
If you do this

758
00:54:27,059 --> 00:54:29,752
they better be paying you this time.

759
00:54:31,335 --> 00:54:34,493
'Cause I can't work any more hours
and look after Peter.

760
00:54:34,494 --> 00:54:38,291
The IRS have the garage,
I'm not losing my home.

761
00:54:38,748 --> 00:54:40,768
It's 200 a day

762
00:54:43,149 --> 00:54:45,035
plus expenses.

763
00:54:47,502 --> 00:54:49,190
Are you shitting me?

764
00:54:49,191 --> 00:54:51,778
But, I haven't decided.

765
00:54:54,244 --> 00:54:56,547
200 dollars a day?

766
00:54:58,663 --> 00:55:00,512
Are you nuts?

767
00:55:23,437 --> 00:55:25,506
This is ridiculous.

768
00:55:27,773 --> 00:55:30,912
Grabbing air. That's the problem.

769
00:55:31,782 --> 00:55:35,470
Over 90, air's getting in, not getting out.

770
00:55:35,471 --> 00:55:37,557
It's the nose.
I can feel it in the wheel.

771
00:55:37,558 --> 00:55:39,964
Mr. Miles, if there's a problem
the computer will find it.

772
00:55:40,338 --> 00:55:43,734
Charlie, get some scotch tape
and a ball of wool.

773
00:55:44,681 --> 00:55:45,681
Alright.

774
00:55:45,942 --> 00:55:50,806
Good, good good. So now let's just
get all of this junk out.

775
00:55:51,109 --> 00:55:52,181
All right, Pops?

776
00:55:52,182 --> 00:55:54,382
Yeah, yeah. I concur.
Come on guys.

777
00:55:57,148 --> 00:55:58,608
What are they doing?

778
00:55:58,765 --> 00:56:00,443
Making your car faster.

779
00:56:07,991 --> 00:56:10,717
There, right there.
Airflow's getting stuck.

780
00:56:13,440 --> 00:56:16,261
I see it. Yarn blows straight up.

781
00:56:16,261 --> 00:56:18,902
- Yep.
<i>- Front's lifting. Damn, he's right.</i>

782
00:56:30,049 --> 00:56:33,405
This car wants to go faster. I feel it.

783
00:56:33,405 --> 00:56:35,835
<i>Any lighter we're getting fragile.</i>

784
00:56:35,836 --> 00:56:37,919
We took 70 pounds out
of her in the last week.

785
00:56:37,919 --> 00:56:41,040
She's outputting max horsepower
from this displacement.

786
00:56:41,606 --> 00:56:44,923
- So put in a bigger engine.
- Where we gonna put it? On the roof?

787
00:56:46,981 --> 00:56:51,508
Managed to make it 52 pounds lighter
than the NASCAR unit.

788
00:56:56,050 --> 00:56:58,468
All new aluminum cylinder heads.

789
00:56:59,263 --> 00:57:02,588
Vibration dampers, Water pump,
Smaller valves.

790
00:57:02,588 --> 00:57:04,864
We call it 'The Beast'.

791
00:57:04,864 --> 00:57:09,353
I can see why, but how's it gonna fit
without redesigning the engine bed?

792
00:57:09,353 --> 00:57:12,140
Well, it certainly wasn't easy.
Good Morning, gentlemen, Mr. Shelby.

793
00:57:12,140 --> 00:57:16,381
So, you already put that in a GT-40?

794
00:57:17,024 --> 00:57:18,987
I'm afraid we have.

795
00:57:24,457 --> 00:57:26,444
<i>I'll be damned.</i>

796
00:57:26,444 --> 00:57:27,623
Well, it's heavy, of course.

797
00:57:27,624 --> 00:57:30,413
Problems with the handling especially
the stopping. I can show you the data.

798
00:57:30,414 --> 00:57:31,465
What problem?

799
00:57:31,466 --> 00:57:33,964
- Understeers a little, but...
- Can I borrow that?

800
00:57:34,558 --> 00:57:36,043
Just a second, thank you.

801
00:57:36,043 --> 00:57:38,074
Ken, Ken!

802
00:57:38,682 --> 00:57:40,751
Perhaps we ought to check
with HQ before you take...

803
00:57:40,752 --> 00:57:43,242
- What'd he say?
- We should ask...

804
00:57:43,698 --> 00:57:45,120
Alright.

805
00:57:48,321 --> 00:57:49,521
Oh, yes!

806
00:57:57,385 --> 00:57:59,826
Mr. Shelby. Welcome to Dearborn.

807
00:57:59,827 --> 00:58:01,003
What are you doing
at a test track?

808
00:58:01,004 --> 00:58:03,270
You're gonna get Castrol
all over that nice suit.

809
00:58:04,012 --> 00:58:06,175
I want to hear your thoughts
on a few planning decisions.

810
00:58:06,175 --> 00:58:07,745
You know, personnel for Le Mans.

811
00:58:07,745 --> 00:58:09,378
Well, It's a hell of a line up,

812
00:58:09,378 --> 00:58:12,913
Ken Miles, Phil Hill,
Chris Amon, Bruce McLaren.

813
00:58:12,914 --> 00:58:15,442
Hill's a lock,  Amon, McLaren too.

814
00:58:15,442 --> 00:58:17,210
We're less sure about Miles.

815
00:58:17,211 --> 00:58:21,827
We like Richie Ginter,
Masten Gregory, Bob Bondurant?

816
00:58:22,338 --> 00:58:26,798
You want the best driver for the car,
who understands the machine, that's Ken.

817
00:58:26,798 --> 00:58:29,509
<i>Oh, Yes!</i>

818
00:58:30,435 --> 00:58:33,764
More of that, please.
More of that, my girl.

819
00:58:33,765 --> 00:58:37,628
<i>I may not get the finer points of racing
Mr. Shelby, but I do know people.</i>

820
00:58:37,991 --> 00:58:42,260
Miles is...He's a beatnik.
He dresses like one.

821
00:58:43,071 --> 00:58:46,822
Ford means reliability.
Ken Miles is not a Ford man.

822
00:58:46,822 --> 00:58:48,538
Whoa!

823
00:58:48,539 --> 00:58:50,675
Giddyup, giddyup!

824
00:58:53,916 --> 00:58:56,011
What's the lap record here, Burt?

825
00:58:56,012 --> 00:58:57,392
1.58.

826
00:58:58,332 --> 00:58:59,781
1.50, dead.

827
00:58:59,781 --> 00:59:00,789
<i>A beatnik? </i>

828
00:59:00,790 --> 00:59:03,280
That man landed a busted
tank on the beach at D-Day

829
00:59:03,281 --> 00:59:05,554
and drove it clean
across Europe to Berlin.

830
00:59:06,326 --> 00:59:07,655
A beatnik?

831
00:59:08,146 --> 00:59:09,615
You know, Lee here asked me a while back,

832
00:59:09,615 --> 00:59:11,334
what's the one thing money can't buy.

833
00:59:12,313 --> 00:59:13,518
I'll tell you what it is.

834
00:59:13,818 --> 00:59:16,218
A pure racer behind
the wheel of your car.

835
00:59:16,802 --> 00:59:18,527
That's Ken Miles.

836
00:59:20,059 --> 00:59:22,277
Well, be that as it may,

837
00:59:22,538 --> 00:59:25,002
we think he may be too pure.

838
00:59:32,419 --> 00:59:35,751
Carroll, do not lose sight
of the big picture here.

839
00:59:36,873 --> 00:59:38,187
Too pure?

840
00:59:39,104 --> 00:59:40,787
What exactly does that mean?

841
00:59:41,574 --> 00:59:43,663
Means he's all about himself.

842
00:59:44,857 --> 00:59:49,184
ABC puts a microphone under his nose.
Perhaps there's a detail he dislikes.

843
00:59:49,184 --> 00:59:50,558
Millions watching.

844
00:59:50,558 --> 00:59:53,008
Do you trust him not to put out
the wrong message?

845
00:59:53,009 --> 00:59:55,483
Well look, you could get a clean
cut all American poster boy.

846
00:59:55,484 --> 00:59:58,010
And stick him behind the wheel.
Teach him what to say.

847
00:59:58,010 --> 01:00:01,256
Shit, you get Doris Day to drive the car
if all you wanna do is lose.

848
01:00:01,576 --> 01:00:04,577
So, you don't agree with us
on this issue?

849
01:00:06,913 --> 01:00:09,240
I'm saying you're gotta trust me
on this one.

850
01:00:09,649 --> 01:00:12,705
Carroll, with marketing concerns,
that's just not possible.

851
01:00:14,339 --> 01:00:18,041
Put a Ford type driver
in a Ford car, Mr. Shelby.

852
01:00:18,267 --> 01:00:20,366
That's the Ford way.

853
01:00:26,419 --> 01:00:29,142
<i>Yet another championship win for Ferrari...</i>

854
01:00:32,034 --> 01:00:33,576
Ferrari wins.

855
01:00:36,893 --> 01:00:38,571
Wedges, we have wedges.

856
01:00:38,805 --> 01:00:40,155
Good, good, good.

857
01:00:40,716 --> 01:00:42,040
Perfect.

858
01:00:42,982 --> 01:00:44,597
- 40?
- Yup.

859
01:00:54,201 --> 01:00:55,325
Hey, boss.

860
01:00:56,737 --> 01:00:58,307
You got a passport?

861
01:00:58,308 --> 01:01:00,493
- What's that?
- Sign that, Get a passport.

862
01:01:00,800 --> 01:01:02,663
Get it back to me by Friday.
Frosty.

863
01:01:02,875 --> 01:01:04,848
Boys, I'm going to France.

864
01:01:06,362 --> 01:01:07,438
Phil.

865
01:01:07,597 --> 01:01:09,730
Ken, can I get a word?

866
01:01:18,008 --> 01:01:19,564
Can I take this?

867
01:01:21,286 --> 01:01:26,269
Do you know why Ford named it the GT-40?
Why they put that 40 on there?

868
01:01:26,269 --> 01:01:28,365
- No.
- Regulations.

869
01:01:28,365 --> 01:01:33,998
We gotta be 40 inches high
to make the ground clearance requirements.

870
01:01:33,998 --> 01:01:36,685
No more, no less.
They measure it before every race.

871
01:01:36,686 --> 01:01:42,262
Problem is that with that height
there's too much drag under the car.

872
01:01:42,262 --> 01:01:43,356
So...

873
01:01:43,357 --> 01:01:46,117
We have a solution, Wedges.
We put wedges in...

874
01:01:46,118 --> 01:01:47,803
You're not coming next week.

875
01:01:50,668 --> 01:01:52,992
You're not coming, Ken.

876
01:01:55,422 --> 01:01:58,269
We're taking McLaren,
Chris Amon, Phil Hill

877
01:01:59,344 --> 01:02:01,291
and Bob Bondurant.

878
01:02:01,703 --> 01:02:03,117
This is Ford's call.

879
01:02:04,536 --> 01:02:06,965
It is their opinion that
you are not a good image,

880
01:02:06,966 --> 01:02:08,794
so you cannot drive their race car.

881
01:02:10,688 --> 01:02:13,449
Putting aside the fact that you made
that car whatever the hell it is,

882
01:02:14,525 --> 01:02:17,540
and you're the best man I got
behind the wheel.

883
01:02:37,193 --> 01:02:39,268
I'm gonna re-route the oil line.

884
01:02:39,268 --> 01:02:42,964
If there's spillage it could drip
onto the rear near side disc.

885
01:02:42,964 --> 01:02:44,013
Ken.

886
01:02:44,013 --> 01:02:49,477
Tell the boys to watch
their pace come sunrise.

887
01:02:49,477 --> 01:02:53,238
The gearbox will overheat.

888
01:03:11,010 --> 01:03:13,626
Ken, race is starting soon.
Want it on the radio?

889
01:03:13,807 --> 01:03:15,713
Not unless you do.

890
01:03:35,648 --> 01:03:38,287
<i>There they are the Maserati
going into the esses,</i>

891
01:03:38,287 --> 01:03:40,444
<i>but it's still the #2 car
driven by Chris Amon.</i>

892
01:03:40,445 --> 01:03:44,115
<i>In third place is the #1 Ford
driven by Bruce McLaren.</i>

893
01:03:44,115 --> 01:03:46,533
<i>A tremendously fast start for the Ford GT.</i>

894
01:03:46,534 --> 01:03:50,728
<i>3:43.4 lap for car #2 Ford.</i>

895
01:03:50,729 --> 01:03:53,625
<i>I think it's a little bit quick
for this stage of the game.</i>

896
01:03:54,721 --> 01:03:56,026
Racing too hot?

897
01:04:04,969 --> 01:04:06,640
<i>Another Ford has come in to the pit</i>

898
01:04:06,641 --> 01:04:09,139
<i>it is being pushed into
the pit by the mechanic.</i>

899
01:04:09,140 --> 01:04:13,227
Head gasket.
The car's not a moon rocket.

900
01:04:16,271 --> 01:04:18,715
<i>Leading #20 Ferrari of Michael Fahr.</i>

901
01:04:18,715 --> 01:04:21,434
So, we have Fords running one,
two, three, how about that?

902
01:04:21,434 --> 01:04:24,264
Too soon, surely too soon.

903
01:04:41,383 --> 01:04:44,049
<i>Here's the big story,
the lead Ford driven by</i>

904
01:04:44,050 --> 01:04:47,557
<i>Rickie Getzer retires with
gearbox trouble and the new leader...</i>

905
01:04:47,558 --> 01:04:52,500
Gearbox.
I told them to be gentle with it.

906
01:04:57,642 --> 01:04:59,197
Who's there?

907
01:05:09,939 --> 01:05:12,103
What's that you're listening to?

908
01:05:12,228 --> 01:05:14,664
Some race over in France.

909
01:05:17,625 --> 01:05:18,955
Excited?

910
01:05:19,658 --> 01:05:22,501
Not really paying much attention.

911
01:05:39,397 --> 01:05:41,690
It's not exactly Champagne.

912
01:05:44,205 --> 01:05:46,096
But it's got bubbles.

913
01:06:15,365 --> 01:06:17,274
Thanks, Mollie.

914
01:07:01,889 --> 01:07:03,558
Grace?

915
01:07:10,655 --> 01:07:11,926
Yes, sir?

916
01:07:12,319 --> 01:07:14,409
I will send him right in.

917
01:07:14,409 --> 01:07:16,433
<i>Thank you.</i>

918
01:07:18,334 --> 01:07:21,286
Mr. Shelby, Mr. Ford will see you now.

919
01:07:21,594 --> 01:07:23,191
Alright.

920
01:07:24,335 --> 01:07:25,503
This guy...

921
01:07:27,338 --> 01:07:29,335
This way, Mr. Shelby.

922
01:07:38,789 --> 01:07:41,690
Mr. Ford, gentlemen.

923
01:07:41,966 --> 01:07:43,526
<i>Shelby.</i>

924
01:07:56,071 --> 01:07:59,036
Give me one reason why
I don't fire everyone

925
01:07:59,037 --> 01:08:02,241
associated with this
abomination, starting with you.

926
01:08:08,934 --> 01:08:10,955
Well, sir.

927
01:08:11,371 --> 01:08:14,001
I was thinking about that very question

928
01:08:14,002 --> 01:08:16,267
as I sat out there in
your lovely waiting room.

929
01:08:17,856 --> 01:08:21,683
As I was sitting there, 
I watched that little red folder

930
01:08:21,684 --> 01:08:25,406
right there go
through four pairs of hands

931
01:08:26,723 --> 01:08:28,488
before it got to you.

932
01:08:28,727 --> 01:08:30,782
Of course, that don't include

933
01:08:30,782 --> 01:08:33,154
<i>the 22 or so other Ford employees</i>

934
01:08:33,154 --> 01:08:36,149
<i>who probably poked at it before it
made its way up to the 19th floor.</i>

935
01:08:38,135 --> 01:08:42,964
With all due respect, sir,
you can't win a race by committee.

936
01:08:44,248 --> 01:08:46,494
<i>You need one man in charge.</i>

937
01:08:46,674 --> 01:08:51,591
Now, the good news, as I see it,
is that even with all the extra weight

938
01:08:53,297 --> 01:08:57,095
we still managed to put ol' Mr. Ferrari
exactly where we want him.

939
01:08:58,183 --> 01:09:00,640
- Did we?
- Oh, yes.

940
01:09:02,764 --> 01:09:04,818
Expand.

941
01:09:05,495 --> 01:09:06,764
Well,

942
01:09:08,350 --> 01:09:10,035
sure, we haven't...

943
01:09:10,489 --> 01:09:12,951
We haven't worked out
how to corner yet.

944
01:09:13,790 --> 01:09:15,404
Or stay cool,

945
01:09:15,404 --> 01:09:18,282
<i>or stay on the ground.</i>

946
01:09:18,282 --> 01:09:20,515
And a lot of stuff broke.

947
01:09:21,026 --> 01:09:24,159
In fact, the only thing that didn't break
was the brakes.

948
01:09:24,160 --> 01:09:25,998
Hell, right now, we don't even know

949
01:09:25,999 --> 01:09:28,566
if our paint job will
last the whole 24 hours.

950
01:09:34,729 --> 01:09:40,984
But our last lap, we clocked 218 mph
down the Mulsanne straight.

951
01:09:40,984 --> 01:09:44,640
Now, in all his years of racing,

952
01:09:45,125 --> 01:09:49,252
ol' Enzo ain't never seen
anything move that fast.

953
01:09:49,814 --> 01:09:53,461
And now he knows without a doubt,

954
01:09:54,652 --> 01:09:56,851
we're faster than he is.

955
01:10:00,048 --> 01:10:04,451
Even with the wrong driver
and all the committees.

956
01:10:05,997 --> 01:10:07,902
And that's what he's thinking about

957
01:10:07,903 --> 01:10:11,684
while he's sitting in
Modena, Italy right now.

958
01:10:14,059 --> 01:10:16,253
That man is scared to death

959
01:10:17,094 --> 01:10:21,766
that this year you actually
might be smart enough to start trusting me.

960
01:10:24,298 --> 01:10:25,899
So, yeah.

961
01:10:27,381 --> 01:10:30,651
I'd say you got Ferrari
exactly where you want him.

962
01:10:34,117 --> 01:10:35,602
You're welcome.

963
01:10:53,163 --> 01:10:54,726
Come here.

964
01:11:02,212 --> 01:11:04,642
You see that little building down there?

965
01:11:04,643 --> 01:11:10,708
In World War II, three out of five
US bombers rolled off that line.

966
01:11:12,930 --> 01:11:17,751
You think Roosevelt beat Hitler?
Think again.

967
01:11:17,751 --> 01:11:21,761
This isn't the first time
Ford Motor's gone to war in Europe.

968
01:11:23,455 --> 01:11:26,267
We know how to do more
than push paper.

969
01:11:28,342 --> 01:11:31,938
And there is one man
running this company.

970
01:11:33,349 --> 01:11:35,501
You report to him.

971
01:11:36,078 --> 01:11:37,908
You understand me?

972
01:11:38,072 --> 01:11:39,812
Yes, sir.

973
01:11:40,470 --> 01:11:43,600
Go ahead, Carroll. Go to war.

974
01:11:46,170 --> 01:11:47,945
Thank you, sir.

975
01:12:20,272 --> 01:12:22,961
You were right.
It's the gearbox.

976
01:12:23,630 --> 01:12:25,327
We ran too hot.

977
01:12:26,139 --> 01:12:30,053
Three out of four of 'em broke.
Rod blew on other one.

978
01:12:34,986 --> 01:12:37,019
We're goin' back, Ken.

979
01:12:40,383 --> 01:12:43,988
They told me I had
<i>a carte blanche</i> this time.

980
01:12:45,355 --> 01:12:48,125
I looked it up,
it's French for 'horse shit'.

